955 CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE IOWA CITY, Ia. — The wounded grew for Iowa on Saturday, but — most importantly — so did the win total.
The No. 22 Hawkeyes rode Jordan Canzeri’s career game to grind out a 29-20 victory over Illinois to improve to 6-0 in front of 66,693 fans at Kinnick Stadium.
Canzeri’s 75-yard run helped break open a tight game late in the third quarter, and Iowa will carry a 2-0 conference record into next week’s Big Ten Conference West Division showdown at No. 13 Northwestern.
The Hawkeyes (6-0, 2-0) had to sweat this one out after injuries took out starting right tackle Ike Boettger and defensive end Drew Ott on a day that started for Iowa without running back LeShun Daniels Jr. (high-ankle sprain), Boone Myers (stinger) and Tevaun Smith (knee).
After Canzeri uncorked Iowa’s longest run from scrimmage since Shonn Greene in 2008 for a 23-13 lead, Illinois (4-2, 1-1) got a little too cute on the first play of the fourth quarter. After Wes Lunt spent much of the third quarter dicing up Iowa’s secondary, Illinois tried a reverse pass with Geronimo Allison. He threw an ugly interception to cornerback Greg Mabin on third-and-1.
But after Illinois responded to slice the gap to 23-20, Iowa answered with an all-out rushing assault behind Canzeri and a makeshift line that was without either of its starting tackles. Canzeri finished with a school-record 43 carries for 256 yards, with the fifth-year senior running Iowa twice into position for two Marshall Koehn field goals. One of those came after a key Josey Jewell fumble recovery at Illinois' 29-yard line.
Illinois' last drive failed behind Lunt, who finished 25-of-41 for 317 yards.
